issues.description:
Delete-after-write atomicity gap: source files are added to `deletions` array at convert-time but only unlinked at the very end of the script. If the process is killed between the last `writeFile(webp, outBuf)` and the final `for (const f of deletions) await unlink(f)` loop, the webp exists but so does the original — harmless. However if `sharp` throws mid-buffer but the `writeFile` already wrote a truncated/corrupt webp, the source is still queued for deletion and will be deleted in the final loop. There is no verification that the written webp is valid before queuing deletion.

Problematic lines:
```js
await writeFile(webp, outBuf);
outSize = outBuf.byteLength;
if (DELETE_ORIGINALS) deletions.push(src);
```

issues.fix:
Verify the written file's size matches the buffer before queuing for deletion, and wrap in a try/catch that skips the deletion queue on error:
```js
try {
  const inBuf = await readFile(src);
  const outBuf = await sharp(inBuf)
    .rotate()
    .resize({ width: MAX_WIDTH, height: MAX_HEIGHT, fit: 'inside', withoutEnlargement: true })
    .webp({ quality: QUALITY, effort: EFFORT })
    .toBuffer();
  await writeFile(webp, outBuf);
  // Verify written size before queuing deletion
  const written = await stat(webp);
  if (written.size !== outBuf.byteLength) throw new Error(`Size mismatch after write: ${webp}`);
  outSize = outBuf.byteLength;
  if (DELETE_ORIGINALS) deletions.push(src);
} catch (err) {
  console.error(`FAILED ${rel}: ${err.message}`);
  continue;
}
```

issues.description:
DRY_RUN mode still populates `deletions` for the 'upToDate / cached' path, causing the dry-run deletion count to be inflated by already-converted files that were merely skipped. More importantly, in non-DRY_RUN mode with `--delete-originals`, a file whose webp is already up-to-date is queued for deletion in the same block where we `continue` — meaning already-converted files get their originals deleted on every subsequent run, defeating idempotency.

Problematic code:
```js
if (upToDate && !DRY_RUN) {
  ...
  if (DELETE_ORIGINALS) deletions.push(src);  // <-- deletes already-cached originals every run
  continue;
}
```

issues.fix:
Only queue deletions for files that were actually converted in this run, not for cached/skipped ones — unless that's intentional, in which case document it clearly. If the intent is 'delete originals only for newly converted files':
```js
if (upToDate && !DRY_RUN) {
  // already up-to-date, no deletion queued
  ...
  continue;
}
```
If the intent is 'delete all originals that have a corresponding webp' (a clean-up sweep), add a separate clearly-named pass after conversion.

issues.description:
Race condition in boot(): the watchdog alert toast fires after a fixed 3500ms timeout, but `fetchSnapshot()` is async and may not have resolved yet on slow connections or cold Vercel starts (cold start can easily exceed 3.5 s). When it hasn't resolved, `state.snapshot` is `null`, so `state.snapshot.alerts` is never read and no toast fires — the real issue is the inverse: if the snapshot resolves *after* 3.5 s, the user never sees the watchdog alert toast.

Problematic code:
```js
setTimeout(() => {
  const alerts = (state.snapshot && state.snapshot.alerts) || [];
  const wd = alerts.find(a => /watchdog|cron/i.test(String(a)));
  if (wd) { toast(wd, 'amber'); sfxBoss(); }
}, 3500);
```

issues.fix:
Move the watchdog toast into `fetchSnapshot()` itself, triggered on the first successful load:
```js
async function fetchSnapshot() {
  const isFirstLoad = !state.snapshot;
  try {
    ...
    state.snapshot = normalizeSnapshot(raw);
    state.snapshotErr = null;
    state.snapshotAt = Date.now();
    if (isFirstLoad) checkWatchdogToast();
  } catch (e) { ... }
  ...
}
function checkWatchdogToast() {
  const alerts = (state.snapshot && state.snapshot.alerts) || [];
  const wd = alerts.find(a => /watchdog|cron/i.test(String(a)));
  if (wd) { toast(wd, 'amber'); sfxBoss(); }
}
```
Remove the `setTimeout` in `boot()`.

issues.description:
`setView()` contains a dead first loop that computes an incorrect `isActive` value (the `.slice(4)` arithmetic is wrong — `'VIEW' + 'TITLE'.toUpperCase()).slice(4)` yields `'TITLE'` coincidentally for 'TITLE' but fails for 'MAP' → gives `'P'` and 'SECTOR' → `'OR'`), then immediately overwrites the work with three explicit toggle lines. The first loop's DOM writes are therefore wrong for MAP and SECTOR views before being immediately corrected, causing two style recalculations and potential flash.

Problematic code:
```js
['Title','Map','Sector'].forEach(name => {
  const id = 'view' + name;
  const node = $(id);
  if (!node) return;
  const isActive = ('VIEW' + name.toUpperCase()).slice(4) === v;  // WRONG for MAP, SECTOR
  node.classList.toggle('active', isActive);
});
// The above is buggy if names mismatch -- explicit map:
$('viewTitle').classList.toggle('active', v === 'TITLE');
$('viewMap').classList.toggle('active', v === 'MAP');
$('viewSector').classList.toggle('active', v === 'SECTOR');
```

issues.fix:
Remove the broken first loop entirely since the three explicit lines below it are correct:
```js
function setView(v) {
  $('viewTitle').classList.toggle('active', v === 'TITLE');
  $('viewMap').classList.toggle('active', v === 'MAP');
  $('viewSector').classList.toggle('active', v === 'SECTOR');
  state.view = v;
  renderTopbar();
  renderWizardPop();
}
```

issues.description:
`_spokenTo` Set is lazily initialised inside `renderSector()` rather than at state initialisation. Since `renderSector()` is called both on `enterSector()` and on snapshot refresh (`if (state.view === 'SECTOR') renderSector()`), the Set will survive refreshes because `state._spokenTo` persists on the object. However if `renderSector()` were ever called before `enterSector()` (e.g. during a future refactor), `state._spokenTo` would be re-initialised, clearing spoken history.

Problematic code:
```js
if (!state._spokenTo) state._spokenTo = new Set();
if (!state._spokenTo.has(sec.id)) {
  state._spokenTo.add(sec.id);
  setTimeout(() => talkToNpc(sec), 300);
}
```

The redirect `window.location.replace('/game.html')` is followed by `return`, but this is inside an inline `<script>` block. `return` in a top-level script (non-module, non-function) is a syntax error in strict mode and throws in some engines (V8 prior to certain versions in some contexts). While most browsers tolerate it in classic inline scripts, it's non-standard. More critically: if `localStorage.getItem` throws (e.g. in a sandboxed iframe or Safari ITP private mode), the entire try/catch means the redirect silently fails and the user lands on the normal command-center view — which is probably the desired fallback, but there's no visual indication or logging.

Problematic code:
```js
if (m === '8bit') {
  window.location.replace('/game.html');
  return;  // non-standard in top-level script
}```

issues.fix:
Wrap in an IIFE to make `return` valid, and add a console.warn for the error case:
```js
(function() {
  try {
    var m = localStorage.getItem('ry_ui_mode');
    if (m === '8bit') {
      window.location.replace('/game.html');
      return;
    } else if (m === 'agent') {
      document.documentElement.classList.add('mode-agent');
      window.__RY_AGENT__ = true;
    }
  } catch(e) {
    console.warn('RY: mode detection failed', e);
  }
})();
```

Add `ontouchstart` or a `pointerenter` handler on each map tile to update focused state on touch hover, and consider adding swipe detection on the map view for left/right/up/down sector navigation:
```js
const tile = el('div', {
  class: '...',
  'data-sector': sec.id,
  onclick: () => { state.focusedSector = i; sfxStep(); enterSector(); },
  onmouseenter: () => { if (state.focusedSector !== i) { state.focusedSector = i; renderMap(); } },
  onpointerenter: () => { if (state.focusedSector !== i) { state.focusedSector = i; renderMap(); } }
}, [...]);
```

Combine into a single `persistSave()` call:
```js
function enterSector() {
  const sec = SECTORS[state.focusedSector];
  if (!sec) return;
  setView('SECTOR');
  sfxOpen();
  if (!state.save.visited_sectors.includes(sec.id)) {
    state.save.visited_sectors.push(sec.id);
  }
  state.save.last_visit_at = new Date().toISOString();
  persistSave(); // single write
  renderSector();
}
```

Add a comment in `openDialogue()` near the speaker/body assignments:
```js
// NOTE: all text is set via .textContent — never switch to innerHTML
// as speaker/body/portrait values can originate from API responses.
$('dialogueSpeaker').textContent = d.speaker;
```
